become part of the common stock of English given names, and was reintroduced from Germany in the 19th century. It was a traditional name among the Hohenstaufens, and was borne by the last  Hohenstaufen king of Sicily  (  1258–66 ), who died in battle against papal forces at Benevento. The name was also used by  Byron  for the central character in his poetic drama Manfred (  1817 ), a brooding outcast, tormented by incestuous love for his half-sister."],"variants":[{"name":"Manfried","meanings":["From an old Germanic personal name, usually said to be from <i>man</i> ‘man’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. However, it is more likely that the first element was <i>magin</i> ‘strength’ (the usual Norman form being <i>Mainfred</i>) or <i>manag</i> ‘much’. This name was in use among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain. However, it did not become part of the common stock of English given names, and was reintroduced from Germany in the 19th century. It was a traditional name among the Hohenstaufens, and was borne by the last  Hohenstaufen king of Sicily  (  1258–66 ), who died in battle against papal forces at Benevento. The name was also used by  Byron  for the central character in his poetic drama Manfred (  1817 ), a brooding outcast, tormented by incestuous love for his half-sister."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Manfred Knyvett was born about 1140, in Southwick, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Drugo Knyvett, was 27 and his mother, Florence Stonner, was 23. He married Isabel Stanhope in 1161, in Southwick, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1163, in Southwick, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"Abt 1140–1163":"umbes 1140–1163","1135–1163":"1135–1163","1137–Male":"1137–Surnud","1140–1163":"1140–1163","1144–Female":"1144–Surnud","1155–1188":"1155–1188","1164–1198":"1164–1198","1115–Male":"1115–Surnud","1119–Female":"1119–Surnud","1198":"1198","1164":"1164","1163":"1163","1140":"1140",